    </figure>
    </statement>
  </example>
</page>

  <page xml:id="vector-algebra">
    <title>Vector Algebra</title>
    <p>
      When we think of an element of <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m> as a vector, we commonly write it as a column:
    </p>
    <me>
      \vec v \;=\; \begin{bmatrix} 1\\ 2\\ 3 \end{bmatrix}.
    </me>
    <p>Suppose <m>c</m> is an arbitrary real number, written <m>c \in \mathbb{R}</m>, and let </p>
    <me>
      \vec u \;=\; \begin{bmatrix} u_1\\ u_2 \end{bmatrix}, 
      \qquad
      \vec v \;=\; \begin{bmatrix} v_1\\ v_2 \end{bmatrix}.
    </me>
    <p>Vectors have the following properties.</p>
    <ol>
      <li>
        <term>Scalar Multiple:</term>
        <me>c\,\vec u \;=\; \begin{bmatrix} c\,u_1\\ c\,u_2 \end{bmatrix}.</me>
      </li>
      <li>
        <term>Vector Addition:</term>
        <me>
          \vec u + \vec v 
          \;=\; \begin{bmatrix} u_1\\ u_2 \end{bmatrix} + \begin{bmatrix} v_1\\ v_2 \end{bmatrix}
          \;=\; \begin{bmatrix} u_1 + v_1\\ u_2 + v_2 \end{bmatrix}.
        </me>
      </li>
    </ol>
    <p workspace="1.5in">
      Vectors in higher dimensions satisfy the same operations componentwise.
    </p>

  </page>

  <page xml:id="lin-comb-span">
    <title>Linear Combinations and Span</title>

    <definition xml:id="def-linear-combination-span" workspace="0.5in">
      <statement>
        <ol>
          <li>
            Given vectors <m>\vec v_1,\vec v_2,\dotsc,\vec v_p \in \mathbb{R}^n</m> and scalars <m>c_1,c_2,\dotsc,c_p</m>, 
            the vector
            <me>
              \vec y \;=\; c_1 \vec v_1 + c_2 \vec v_2 + \cdots + c_p \vec v_p
            </me>
            is called a <term>linear combination</term> of <m>\vec v_1,\dotsc,\vec v_p</m> with weights <m>c_1,\dotsc,c_p</m>.
          </li>
          <li>
            The set of all linear combinations of <m>\vec v_1,\dotsc,\vec v_p</m> is called the <term>span</term> of these vectors.
          </li>
        </ol>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <p>
      Any two vectors in <m>\mathbb{R}^2</m> that are not scalar multiples of one another span <m>\mathbb{R}^2</m>. 
      Thus, any vector in <m>\mathbb{R}^2</m> can be written as a linear combination of such a pair.
    </p>

    <figure xml:id="fig-grid-combos">
      <caption>Linear combinations of two nonparallel vectors spanning the plane.</caption>
      <image xml:id="img-grid-combos" width="60%">
        <description>
        A lightly rotated square grid with the origin and multiples/sums of two non-parallel vectors labeled, 
        illustrating how combinations like <m>\vec v+\vec u</m>, <m>2\vec v+\vec u</m>, etc., tile the plane.
      </description>
        <latex-image>
          <preamble>
          </preamble>
          <tex>
\begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.1]
  \begin{scope}[rotate=5]
    % light grid
    \draw[gray, thin] (0,0)--(8,0) (0,1)--(8,1) (0,2)--(8,2) (0,3)--(8,3);
    \draw[gray, thin] (1,0)--(1,3) (3,0)--(3,3) (5,0)--(5,3) (7,0)--(7,3);
    % origin and vectors
    \node[black] at (3,1) {$\vec 0$};
    \draw[-{Stealth[length=4pt]}, green, very thick] (3,1) -- (5,1) node[anchor=north west] {$\vec u$};
    \node[gray] at (7,1) {$2\vec u$};
    \draw[-{Stealth[length=4pt]}, cyan, very thick] (3,1) -- (3,2) node[anchor=north west] {$\vec v$};
    \draw[-{Stealth[length=4pt]}, blue, very thick] (3,1) -- (5,2) node[anchor=north west] {$\vec v+\vec u$};
    \node[gray] at (7,2) {$\vec v+2\vec u$};
    \node[gray] at (7,3) {$2\vec v+2\vec u$};
    \node[gray] at (5,3) {$2\vec v+\vec u$};
    \node[gray] at (3,3) {$2\vec v$};
    \node[gray] at (1,3) {$2\vec v-\vec u$};
    \node[gray] at (1,2) {$\vec v-\vec u$};
    \node[gray] at (1,1) {$-\vec u$};
    \draw[-{Stealth[length=4pt]}, red, very thick] (3,1) -- (2,2.5) node[anchor=north east] {$1.5\vec v-0.5\vec u$};
  \end{scope}
\end{tikzpicture}
          </tex>
        </latex-image>
      </image>
    </figure>

  </page>

  <page xml:id="examples">
    <title>Examples of Linear Combinations and Span</title>
    
    <example workspace="2in">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>\vec u=\begin{bmatrix} -1\\ 4\\ 2\end{bmatrix}</m> and <m>\vec v=\begin{bmatrix} 5\\ 0\\ -3\end{bmatrix}</m>. Determine three vectors which are linear combinations of <m>\vec u</m> and <m>\vec v</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>

    <example workspace="2in">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>\vec u=\begin{bmatrix} -1\\ 4\\ 2\end{bmatrix}</m> and <m>\vec v=\begin{bmatrix} 5\\ 0\\ -3\end{bmatrix}</m>. Determine if <m>\vec w = \begin{bmatrix} 2 \\ 12 \\ 3 \end{bmatrix}</m> is in <m>\textrm{Span}(\vec u, \vec v)</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>
  </page>

  <page xml:id="example-span">
    <title>Example: Membership in a Span</title>
  <p>
      In general, any two non-parallel vectors in <m>\mathbb{R}^3</m> span a plane through the origin. 
      Every vector in that plane is a linear combination of the two.
    </p>

    <figure xml:id="fig-plane-span">
      <caption>Two nonparallel vectors in <m>\mathbb{R}^3</m> span a plane through the origin.</caption>
      <image xml:id="img-plane-span" width="30%">
        <description>
        A translucent plane through the origin with two nonparallel vectors drawn from the origin; 
        coordinate axes are shown for reference.
      </description>
        <latex-image>
          <preamble>
          </preamble>
          <tex>
\tdplotsetmaincoords{74}{100}
\begin{tikzpicture}[scale=2.4,
  axis/.style={-{Stealth[length=4pt]},black},
  vectorC/.style={-{Stealth[length=4pt]},black,very thick},
  vectorV/.style={-{Stealth[length=4pt]},blue,very thick},
  tdplot_main_coords
]
  \coordinate (O) at (0,0,0);
  \coordinate (X) at (2,0,0);
  \coordinate (Y) at (0,1,0);
  \coordinate (Z) at (0,0,1);
  \coordinate (X1) at (1,1,0);
  \coordinate (X2) at (1,0,1);
  \coordinate (X3) at (2,1,1);

  % plane spanned by X1 and X2
  \filldraw[draw=blue!40,fill=blue!8]
    (0,0,0) -- (1,1,0) -- (2,1,1) -- (1,0,1) -- cycle;

  % axes
  \draw[axis] (O) -- (X);
  \draw[axis] (O) -- (Y);
  \draw[axis] (O) -- (Z);

  % spanning vectors
  \draw[vectorV] (O) -- (X1);
  \draw[vectorV] (O) -- (X2);

  % origin label
  \node[below] at (O) {$\vec 0$};
\end{tikzpicture}
          </tex>
        </latex-image>
      </image>
    </figure>

    <example xml:id="ex-span-membership">
      <statement>
        <p>Is <m>\vec y</m> in the span of <m>\vec v_1</m> and <m>\vec v_2</m>?</p>
        <me>
          \vec v_1 \;=\; \begin{bmatrix} 1\\ -2\\ -3 \end{bmatrix},\qquad
          \vec v_2 \;=\; \begin{bmatrix} 2\\ 5\\ 6 \end{bmatrix},\qquad
          \vec y   \;=\; \begin{bmatrix} 7\\ 4\\ 15 \end{bmatrix}.
        </me>
      </statement>
    </example>
  </page>


